have not described him. This book argues that one must first describe the criminal and then 
define him in order to solve the problem of mistaken identity when it comes to people attempting 
to identify the criminal, which can quite possibly be an inmate. 
4. Anger – Anger is a basic part of the criminal’s way of life. He or she responds angrily to 
anything interpreted as opposing what he or she wants. Anger is, for the criminal, a major 
way of controlling people and situations. 
My Response—Criminals desire to know and not to know thier enviornment; this causes the 
criminal to imagine things other than himself that can control the enviornment. But this in a 
sense, creates anger and this anger doesn’t provide the criminal anything new as an incentive for 
desiring to directly control people or situations. What the criminal wants is clarity not in his life, 
but in his vision. Anger is, for the criminal, a minor truth of control—that what one comprehends 
in some ways determines how successful a person is. This is incomplete evidence however, and 
doesn’t have a relationship to anything. It does mean, moreover, that truth was arrived at without 
meaning.
5. Pride – Criminal pride is an extreme high evaluation of oneself. It is the idea that one is 
better than others, even when this is clearly not the case. Criminal pride preserves his or 
her rigid self-image as a powerful, totally self-determining person.
My Response—Criminals are prideful because they lack a vision—the same with all of us, we 
must never sin just for the sake of sinning. Instead, theirs a purpose for the reason criminals 
exists and that is why we have taken an interests in the way that they think. But to suggest that 
pride is justified by only who the criminal is, as Yochelson and Samenow does, is to say that 
pride is not a sin but is power, in the sense that it is criminal. Reality may confirm to the criminal 
that he is not better than others, but this won’t change the criminal. Pride may change the 
criminal thinking error, when we discover the hope that a criminals personality can change. So 
what we have in criminology is a temporary description of the criminal by employing the 
discipline of psychology in order to understand the personality of the ideal criminal and not the 
criminal reality. What I have just done is introduce you to the criminal reality in response to the 
term criminal pride.
6. The Power Thrust – Criminals need control and power over others. The greatest power 
excitement is doing the forbidden and getting away with it. The need for power, control, 
and dominance shows in all areas of their lives. The occasions when criminals appear to 
show an interest in a responsible activity are generally opportunities for criminals to 
exercise power and control. 
My Response—In one way Yochelson and Samenow are correct, criminals need power over 
others but why do they need? Criminals in some way, already have control and Yochelson and 
Samenow have not explained why they need it over others. Does social control oppose the 
criminal? The need for control only partially shows in criminals and Yochelson and Samenow 
have not convincingly demonstrated the criminal. 7. Sentimentality – Criminals are often excessively sentimental about their mothers, old 
people, invalids, animals, babies, their love attachments, and plans for the future
My Response—Criminals live in a isolated world, and they learn habits that will be considered 
abnormal to society and to their culture—that is the culture that welcomed them in.
8. Religion – Criminals use religion to support their way of thinking and their criminality. 
Their religious ideas are usually very literal and concrete. Religion (like sentimentality) 
does not consistently deter criminal thinking or actions, but does support the criminal’s 
self-image as a good and decent person. 
My Response—This is the best description that Yochelson and Samenow have given regarding 
the criminal. However, the criminal knows that he is not liked by society.
9. Concrete Thinking – Criminals tend to think in terms of particular objects and events, 
rather than general and abstract concepts. 
My Response—Criminals view education as a game. Information is obtained by the games that 
they play.
Criminal thinking is the only remedy that our customs view as indicative of the vision that we
